@conradz and @jonnyreeves  sorry for the delay. This just landed on v0.8.0. Now on node.js you can do:

``` js
var Signal = require('signals');
var onAwesome = new Signal();
// ...
```

and on AMD:

``` js
define(['signals'], function(Signal){
   var onAwesome = new Signal();
   // ...
});
```

On the browser it still exposes a single global `signals`.

``` js
var onAwesome = new signals.Signal();
```

Legacy code should keep working since the `Signal` constructor is also exposed as a property of itself:

``` js
// this will keep working
var Signal = require('signals').Signal;
```

Another solution is to add a new method to the `dispatch()` function that does the binding:

``` js
function Signal(){
  var self = this;
  this.dispatch.bind = function(){
    return function(){
      self.dispatch.apply(self, arguments);
    };
  };
  // ...
}
```

Which would be used like this:

``` js
$('#foo').fadeOut( 500, ended.dispatch.bind() );
```

I like the _automagical_ approach better - calling `bind()` without any argument fells weird and user might not know he needs to do that.

